{
    "metadata": {
        "title": "Executable Code Actions Elicit Better LLM Agents",
        "author": "Xingyao Wang, Yangyi Chen, Lifan Yuan, Yizhe Zhang, Yunzhu Li, Hao Peng, Heng Ji",
        "publish_date": "PMLR 235, 2024",
        "organization": "University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, Apple"
    },
    "sections": [
        {
            "title": "Abstract",
            "subsections": [
                {
                    "title": "Overview of CodeAct and Key Findings",
                    "content": "Large Language Model (LLM) agents show potential in real-world challenges but are often limited by action generation via JSON or text, which constrains action spaces and flexibility. This work proposes CodeAct, using executable Python code as a unified action space. CodeAct, integrated with a Python interpreter, can dynamically revise prior actions or emit new ones based on new observations through multi-turn interactions. It leverages existing libraries and automated feedback for self-debugging. Extensive analysis of 17 LLMs on APIBank and a new benchmark (M³ToolEval) shows CodeAct outperforms widely used alternatives (up to 20% higher success rate). To foster development, we introduce CodeActInstruct, an instruction-tuning dataset of 7k multi-turn interactions using CodeAct. This dataset improves models in agent-oriented tasks without compromising general capabilities. CodeActAgent, fine-tuned from Llama2 and Mistral, is integrated with a Python interpreter and is uniquely tailored to perform sophisticated tasks (e.g., model training) using existing libraries and autonomously self-debug."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "Introduction: The Need for Better LLM Agent Actions",
            "subsections": [
                {
                    "title": "Limitations of Current Approaches & The CodeAct Solution",
                    "content": "LLM agents typically generate actions as JSON or text in pre-defined formats. This approach often suffers from constrained action spaces (limited by pre-defined tools) and restricted flexibility (e.g., inability to compose multiple tools). We propose CodeAct, a framework where LLM agents generate executable Python code as their actions. This unified action space offers distinct advantages: 1) **Dynamic Interaction**: Integrated with a Python interpreter, CodeAct executes code actions and allows dynamic adjustment of prior actions or emission of new actions based on observations like code execution results. 2) **Expanded Capabilities**: Code actions enable LLMs to leverage the vast ecosystem of existing Python packages, rather than relying on handcrafted, task-specific tools. Automated feedback, such as error messages from the interpreter, facilitates self-debugging. 3) **Inherent LLM Familiarity**: Modern LLMs are pre-trained on extensive code data, making code a natural output modality. 4) **Complex Operations**: Python code inherently supports control flow (loops, conditionals) and data flow (variables), allowing for the composition of multiple tools and complex logical operations within a single action. This unlocks LLMs' potential for sophisticated task-solving. Our findings indicate that CodeAct leads to up to 20% higher success rates and requires up to 30% fewer actions in complex scenarios."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "CodeAct: Executable Code as the Action Language",
            "subsections": [
                {
                    "title": "The CodeAct Interaction Framework",
                    "content": "CodeAct operates within a general multi-turn interaction framework involving three roles: the agent, the user, and the environment. In each turn, the agent receives an observation (e.g., user instruction or environment feedback), optionally plans its action (e.g., via chain-of-thought), and then emits an action. For agent-environment interactions, CodeAct employs Python code to consolidate all actions. Each action sent to the environment is a piece of Python code, and the agent receives the outputs of code execution (e.g., results, errors) as its next observation, enabling a continuous loop of action and feedback. This framework is depicted conceptually in our agent interaction diagram (Figure 2 in paper)."
                },
                {
                    "title": "Empirical Validation: CodeAct's Superiority",
                    "content": "We conducted extensive experiments with 17 LLMs to validate CodeAct. **Atomic Tool Use (APIBank):** On tasks involving single, atomic tool calls, CodeAct achieved comparable or better performance than JSON and text action formats, particularly for open-source LLMs. This suggests LLMs are already familiar with code structures. **Complex Multi-Tool Tasks (M³ToolEval):** We curated M³ToolEval, a new benchmark with 82 human-curated tasks requiring multi-tool composition and multi-turn interactions (e.g., web browsing, finance). On M³ToolEval, CodeAct demonstrated significant advantages, achieving up to a 20% absolute improvement in success rates over baselines, while requiring up to 30% fewer actions. For instance, gpt-4-1106-preview with CodeAct showed a 20.7% higher success rate and 2.1 fewer turns on average compared to the next best format. These results (visualized in Figure 1 bottom, detailed in Tables 2 & 3 in paper) underscore the benefits of CodeAct's control and data flow capabilities for complex problem-solving."
                },
                {
                    "title": "Leveraging Python's Power: Ecosystem & Self-Debugging",
                    "content": "A key strength of CodeAct is its ability to harness existing software infrastructure. LLM agents using CodeAct can directly import and utilize readily available Python libraries (e.g., Pandas for data manipulation, Scikit-Learn for machine learning, Matplotlib for plotting) to perform complex tasks without requiring custom-built tools or extensive in-context demonstrations. Furthermore, the interactive Python interpreter provides immediate feedback, including error messages and tracebacks when code execution fails. This enables the agent to 'self-debug' its generated code within a multi-turn interaction, autonomously identify and rectify errors, and ultimately complete the user's request successfully. An illustrative example (Figure 3 in paper) showcases CodeActAgent performing model training and data visualization, self-correcting errors along the way."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "Building Capable Agents: CodeActInstruct & CodeActAgent",
            "subsections": [
                {
                    "title": "CodeActInstruct: A Novel Dataset for Agent Fine-Tuning",
                    "content": "To empower open-source LLMs with robust CodeAct capabilities, we developed CodeActInstruct, an instruction-tuning dataset comprising 7,000 high-quality multi-turn interaction trajectories. This dataset covers diverse agent-environment interaction scenarios: **Information Seeking** (using search APIs on HotpotQA), **Software Package (Tool) Usage** (solving APPS coding and MATH problems by importing Python libraries), **External Memory Access** (tabular reasoning on WikiTableQuestion using SQL or Pandas), and **Robot Planning** (completing household tasks in ALFWorld via control APIs). A crucial aspect of CodeActInstruct's creation was a careful data selection process, specifically filtering for trajectories that demonstrate the agent's ability to improve from interaction, such as self-debugging based on error messages. CodeActInstruct is significantly larger and covers more diverse domains than comparable prior datasets (details in Table 4 in paper)."
                },
                {
                    "title": "CodeActAgent: Fine-tuned LLMs for Enhanced Code Actions",
                    "content": "Using our new dataset, we fine-tuned Llama-2 7B and Mistral-7B models on a mixture of CodeActInstruct and general conversation data, resulting in CodeActAgent. **Performance Highlights (based on Table 5 in paper):** CodeActAgent models excelled in tasks requiring CodeAct, outperforming all evaluated open-source LLMs on both in-domain and out-of-domain subsets of the MINT benchmark. The Mistral-based CodeActAgent, in particular, achieved performance comparable to much larger 70B models on the M³ToolEval benchmark when using CodeAct. Notably, CodeActAgent also demonstrated strong generalization to out-of-domain tasks that use traditional text-based actions (e.g., MiniWob++, ScienceWorld), performing on par with models specifically tuned for text actions. Importantly, these agent-specific improvements were achieved while maintaining or even improving performance on a suite of general LLM evaluation tasks (MMLU, HumanEval, GSM8K, MTBench). Ablation studies confirmed that both CodeActInstruct data and general conversation data were vital for these results."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "title": "Conclusion and Key Contributions",
            "subsections": [
                {
                    "title": "Summary of Innovations and Future Outlook",
                    "content": "This work introduces CodeAct, a framework that employs executable Python code as the action mechanism for LLM agents. CodeAct proves advantageous over conventional text or JSON actions, especially in complex scenarios requiring dynamic interaction and leveraging existing software. Our key contributions include: 1) The **CodeAct framework**, enabling robust agent-environment interaction via Python. 2) **M³ToolEval**, a new benchmark for evaluating LLM agents on complex, multi-tool tasks. 3) **CodeActInstruct**, a large-scale, diverse instruction-tuning dataset designed to enhance agents' CodeAct capabilities and self-improvement behaviors. 4) **CodeActAgent**, open-source LLM agents fine-tuned on CodeActInstruct, demonstrating superior performance in CodeAct tasks, strong generalization, and the ability to perform sophisticated operations like model training with self-debugging. Future work will focus on building upon CodeAct to develop even more capable, reliable, and safe autonomous agents for a wider range of real-world applications."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}
